<p>The <b>Metéora</b> (<a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a>: <span lang="el" xml:lang="el">Μετέωρα</span>, "suspended rocks", "suspended in the air" or "in the heavens above") is one of the largest and most important complexes of <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Orthodox" title="Eastern Orthodox" class="mw-redirect">Eastern Orthodox</a> <a href="/wiki/Monastery" title="Monastery">monasteries</a> in Greece, second only to <a href="/wiki/Mount_Athos" title="Mount Athos">Mount Athos</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-meteora_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-meteora-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The nearest town is <a href="/wiki/Kalambaka" title="Kalambaka" class="mw-redirect">Kalambaka</a>, <a href="/wiki/Greece" title="Greece">Greece</a>. The <a href="/wiki/Monastery" title="Monastery">monasteries</a> are built on natural sandstone rock pillars, at the northwestern edge of the <a href="/wiki/Thessaly" title="Thessaly">Plain of Thessaly</a> near the Peneios river and <a href="/wiki/Pindus_Mountains" title="Pindus Mountains" class="mw-redirect">Pindus Mountains</a>, in central <a href="/wiki/Greece" title="Greece">Greece</a>. The Metéora is home to six <a href="/wiki/Monastery" title="Monastery">monasteries</a> and is included on the <a href="/wiki/UNESCO" title="UNESCO">UNESCO</a> <a href="/wiki/World_Heritage_List" title="World Heritage List" class="mw-redirect">World Heritage List</a>. Metéora's <a href="/wiki/World_Heritage_Site#Selection_criteria" title="World Heritage Site">criteria</a><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> for the <a href="/wiki/UNESCO" title="UNESCO">UNESCO</a> World Heritage Site are I, II, IV, V and VII.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
